explanation:
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/inline used to obtain the sem pointer from the token. Need to know how it translates token to an object pointer/index (can it yield NULL or otherwise change control/data flow).
- OS_impl_bin_sem_table: The table passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its layout/contents determine what sem points to and whether removal of operations on the returned object would be observable.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Shown in the static call graph as a callee of this function (likely used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET). Its behavior (bounds checking, mapping, error handling) affects whether sem is valid and whether code paths can be reached/are meaningful.
- OS_object_token_t: The token type (and its representation) is used to index the object table; understanding its semantics is required to reason about whether the lookup is effective or redundant.
- OS_impl_binsem_internal_record_t: Definition of the semaphore record (must include the types and semantics of members sem->cv and sem->id). Knowing the members and their types is necessary to determine whether the pthread destroy operations have observable side effects and whether those operations are redundant.
- pthread_cond_destroy: The POSIX cond-var destroy function and its semantics (return values, failure conditions, side effects). The function return drives control flow (sets OS_SEM_FAILURE vs OS_SUCCESS). To determine if the call is dead, one must know whether it has observable effects and when/why it can fail.
- pthread_mutex_destroy: The POSIX mutex destroy function and its semantics (whether it has observable side effects, possible failure modes). The call is executed unconditionally in one branch; to know if it is dead code we must know whether removing it would change program-observable behaviour.
- OS_SEM_FAILURE and OS_SUCCESS: The numeric return-code constants used as the function result. To decide if assignments/returns are dead we must know what these values mean to callers and whether returning one vs the other affects program behaviour.
